content.content:
In $\triangle ABC$, let $\overline{CD}$ bisect $\angle ACB$, with 
$D$ on $\overline{AB}$.

Draw a line through $A$ parallel to $\overline{CD}$, and extend 
$\overline{BC}$ to meet this line at $E$.

center
tikzpicture[scale=0.7]
 (A) at (0,0);
 (B) at (6,0);
 (C) at (2,3);
 (D) at (2.4,0);
 (E) at (-1.5,2.25);

 (A) – (B) – (C) – cycle;
 (C) – (D);
 (B) – (E);
 (A) – (E);

 ll (A) circle (2pt);
 ll (B) circle (2pt);
 ll (C) circle (2pt);
 ll (D) circle (2pt);
 ll (E) circle (2pt);

 at (A) {$A$};
 at (B) {$B$};
 at (C) {$C$};
 at (D) {$D$};
 at (E) {$E$};
tikzpicture
center

Since $\overline{AE} \parallel \overline{CD}$:

- $\angle AEC \cong \angle DCB$ (corresponding angles)

- $\angle EAC \cong \angle DCA$ (alternate interior angles)

Since $\overline{CD}$ bisects $\angle C$: $\angle DCA \cong \angle DCB$

Therefore: $\angle EAC \cong \angle AEC$

This makes $\triangle AEC$ isosceles with $EA = AC$.

In $\triangle BEA$, since $\overline{CD} \parallel \overline{EA}$:
\[
\frac{BD}{DA} = \frac{BC}{CE} = \frac{BC}{AC}
\]

Taking reciprocals: $\dfrac{AD}{DB} = \dfrac{AC}{BC}$
